            <section id="faq" class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Kite calculator FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded">
                  <summary class="px-3 py-2 cursor-pointer font-medium">
                    What is a kite in geometry?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    In geometry, a kite is a quadrilateral with two pairs of
                    adjacent sides equal in length. The equal sides meet at two
                    vertices, and the diagonals are perpendicular. One diagonal
                    is an axis of symmetry and bisects the other diagonal and
                    the angles between equal sides.
                  </div>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded">
                  <summary class="px-3 py-2 cursor-pointer font-medium">
                    How do I calculate the area of a kite?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    The most convenient formula is \(A = \dfrac{d_1 d_2}{2}\),
                    where \(d_1\) and \(d_2\) are the diagonal lengths. If you
                    know the side lengths and the included angle instead, you
                    can use \(A = a b \sin(\theta)\). The calculator supports
                    both approaches.
                  </div>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded">
                  <summary class="px-3 py-2 cursor-pointer font-medium">
                    Which inputs should I use?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Use the measurements you actually have:
                    <ul class="list-disc ml-5 mt-1">
                      <li>
                        For textbook problems, diagonals are often given – enter
                        \(d_1\) and \(d_2\).
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        For construction or design, you may know side lengths
                        and the angle – enter \(a\), \(b\), and \(\theta\).
                      </li>
                      <li>
                        If you measured one side and both diagonals, enter those
                        three and the calculator will infer the rest.
                      </li>
                    </ul>
                  </div>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded">
                  <summary class="px-3 py-2 cursor-pointer font-medium">
                    Why do I get an “invalid kite” error?
                  </summary>
                  <div class="px-3 pb-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    This happens when the numbers cannot form a valid kite.
                    Common causes include: negative or zero lengths, an angle
                    outside 0–180°, or diagonals and sides that violate the
                    Pythagorean relationships of the right triangles formed by
                    the diagonals. Double‑check your measurements and units.
                  </div>
                </details>
